misplayed it and lost, Leko,P (2763)-Topalov,V (2788)/San Luis 2005. However,
Black has at his disposal the sharp 10...Qa5 11.b3 Bb7 12.a3 Qc7, which leads
to complications which are favourable for him.}) ({Later Leko switched to} 10.
Bc4 {:} Ne5 11. Bb3 Rb8 12. O-O Bd7 13. a3 a5 14. axb4 axb4 15. f4 $36 {1/2-1/
2 Leko,P-Grischuk,A/Moscow 2006 (65)}) 10... bxc3 11. Nxc3 Bb7 12. Be2 Be7 ({
In 2006 Topalov won against Anand after} 12... d5 13. exd5 Nxd5 14. Nxd5 Bxd5
15. O-O Qb8 16. Nf5 Qe5 17. Ng3 Bb4 $1 {but later Morozevich discovered that
Black faces problems after 15.Rc1!.}) 13. O-O O-O 14. Rac1 Qb8 15. Rfd1 Rd8 {
An important move. Although White seems to have more space and therefore some
pressure, Black inevitably advances d5 next and should have no problems
whatsoever.} ({The immediate} 15... d5 {is premature due to} 16. exd5 Nxd5 17.
Nxd5 Bxd5 18. Nc6 $14) 16. Kh1 {This new move changes little: Black has a
comfortable game.} (16. Bf2 {was met once before, after which Black can
continue} d5 17. Bg3 Bd6) 16... d5 17. exd5 Nxd5 18. Nxd5 Bxd5 19. Bc4 ({Now} 
19. Nc6 {is no longer attractive for White due to} Bxc6 20. Rxc6 Ne5 {and
after the forced} 21. Rb6 Qc8 22. Qc1 Rxd1+ 23. Qxd1 Nc4 24. Bxc4 Qxc4 {it is
Black who has some initiative}) (19. a3 Nc5 20. Qc3 (20. b4 $2 Nb3 21. Nxb3
Bxb3 $19) 20... a5 $11) 19... Nf6 20. Qe2 Qb7 21. b3 h6 {The position is
completely equal. In the next part both sides try to improve their pieces.
